[1] Philippines
Date: Mon 17 Sep 2007
Source: Inquirer.net [edited]
<http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/nation/view_article.php?article_id=89116>

The number of dengue cases in the 9 months to September [2007]
dropped 4.6 percent from the same period last year [2006], the
Department of Health (DoH) said Monday [17 Sep 2007].
In a statement, the DoH's National Epidemiology Center (NEC) said 18
705 dengue cases were recorded from January to September [2007]. A
total of 19 601 cases were recorded during the same period last year [2006].
NEC data showed that while the ages of those stricken with dengue
ranged from 18 days to 98 years old, the bulk of cases -- 77 percent
-- involved people between the ages of one and 20. The [slight]
majority of those affected -- 53 percent -- were male.
No dengue hotspots were identified in the latest NEC data but the
clustering of cases was noted in cities such as Manila, Malabon,
Quezon, Caloocan, Muntinlupa, Paranaque, San Juan, and Valenzuela in
the National Capital Region.
Health Secretary Francisco Duque III reminded community officials to
sustain clean-up activities and continue the improvement in the
agency's drive against the disease. "Barangay [village] officials
should not let up in their efforts to rid their communities of
mosquito-breeding places," said Duque in the statement. Duque visited
Barangay 275 in Parola in Binondo on Monday [17 Sep 2007] as part of
the department's dengue inspection. Barangays are expected to remove
non-essential containers in their areas that can hold [water] and
become breeding places of mosquitoes, which carry dengue.
[Byline: Beverly T. Natividad]
