[2] Southeast Asia
Date: Mon 24 Sep 2007
Source: Bangkok Post [edited]
<http://www.bangkokpost.com/240907_News/24Sep2007_news19.php>

The World Health Organisation (WHO) got it right on Wednesday [19 Sep
2007] when it said in Phuket that we should be taking the 33 percent
jump in the number of reported dengue cases this year [2007] a great
deal more seriously. It also chose the right moment to call for
stricter and more effective control measures before the problem gets
out of hand.
The _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito, which transmits dengue fever [viruses],
inflicted its misery on 41 975 people between 1 Jan and 8 Sep [2007]
and killed 47 of them, according to the Public Health Ministry's
Disease Control Department. And these are just the cases we know
about. Indonesia has been hardest-hit with over 160 000 cases, while
Burma [Myanmar] has also seen a surge in infections, totalling 11
577. Cambodia has suffered 25 000 cases this year [2007], killing 300
children under 15 -- 3 times the number in all of 2005. Malaysia has
also seen a 50 percent leap in infections, with 56 deaths recorded in
June [2007] and more than 1000 patients admitted to hospital every
week in July [2007], while Viet Nam has seen a 40 percent jump on
last year [2006], with 33 000 people infected and 32 deaths. In fact,
no country in Southeast Asia has been left untouched and the outbreak
threatens to become the worst in a decade.
Some of the blame for this is put on changing climate conditions
which have affected the life cycle of the mosquito carrier, enabling
it to produce a minimum infective dose of the dengue virus faster
than before. Another factor is the increase in travel and migration
of people and animals which has caused a rise in dengue transmission
across international borders and could be why new strains of the
virus have emerged throughout the world [Non-human animals are not
hosts for dengue viruses, with the possible exception of non-human
primates. Therefore, movement of animals is not a factor in rising
dengue virus transmission. Movement of infected mosquitoes could move
dengue viruses across international borders. - Mod.TY]
The major culprit, though, is rapid urbanisation. This is usually
fuelled by growing prosperity, but we have a home-grown problem
rooted in the past. The grim legacy of the 1997 property market
collapse and financial crisis is still visible in the number of
unfinished buildings in central Bangkok. Of the total 508 structures,
only 380 have been re-developed while the remaining 128 have been
left to decay. Despite repeated safety warnings they remain empty and
abandoned. Abandoned that is except for the pools of unsanitary,
stagnant water which have been allowed to build up, providing ideal
conditions for mosquitoes to breed and create a major health hazard.
This pattern is also visible in regular construction sites with every
puddle, old, unused automobile tyre, discarded plastic bag, or
aluminium can [be] a potential breeding ground.
So what hope is there for an end to this scourge? There is no cure
for either dengue fever or the potentially fatal form called dengue
haemorrhagic fever [DHF], which causes internal bleeding and
circulatory collapse. Attempts are being made to develop a vaccine
effective against the 4 serotypes but production is a long way off.
Epidemiologists are working on ways to combat dengue but the only
surefire method of prevention and control is to eliminate the places
where the mosquitoes breed. And that can only work if we all play a part.
Eradicating them in their breeding grounds means emptying pools of
still water, whether in small pots, jars, bottles, and other areas
where they breed. Mosquitoes never breed in moving water so drains
must be kept clear and flowing. Old vehicle tyres must be disposed
of. If pools of still water cannot be emptied, a coat of oil will
kill underwater larvae by depriving them of oxygen. All this is very
difficult to manage in the rainy season but it is the only effective way.
Sale and distribution of mosquito larvae, commonly known as 'luk
nam', for use as fish food must be outlawed and a public awareness
campaign launched. Nor must there be any repetition of the selfish
incident under the previous government when ornamental fish breeders
in Nakhon Pathom physically blocked health workers from spraying,
saying they needed the mosquito larvae as live feed for their fish.
It was no coincidence that Nakhon Chaisri district, where the fish
breeding business is popular and where this occurred, had the highest
incidence of dengue fever in the province that year.
Health officials, much to our disappointment, have not been very
successful in keeping the city clean of mosquitoes. So it is up to us.
--
